<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="competitive-intelligence-methods">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>market-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Two-sub-methodology bundle: landscape mapping (2x2 + whitespace, 15-20 competitors, four types) then feature-matrix drill-down (Y/P/N + quality score, gap-validation critic, forced skip budget).</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>competitive-intelligence</tag>
      <tag>feature-matrix</tag>
      <tag>competitor-landscape</tag>
      <tag>gap-validation</tag>
      <tag>market-research</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Competitive Intelligence Methods</title>
    <summary>A two-sub-methodology bundle — competitor landscape mapping and competitive-intelligence feature analysis — run as a sequential pipeline: landscape first (2x2 positioning + whitespace identification across 15-20 competitors covering all four types), then feature-matrix drill-down (Y/P/N + 0-3 quality score with evidence URL per cell, gap-validation critic with forced skip budget).</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Teams default to the 3-5 obvious head-on competitors and miss substitutes (spreadsheets, email, "do nothing") — the actual churn cause. A feature matrix with only Y/N hides quality differences; without a gap-validator critic forcing ≥40% skips, pursuit-bias turns every empty cell into a roadmap item. The four-type taxonomy and adversarial critic together produce a defensible gap shortlist.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pre-MVP wedge selection: need the 2x2 + gap list before writing a spec.</item>
        <item>Quarterly competitive review: deltas in funding, pricing, positioning, hiring across top 15-20 competitors.</item>
        <item>New-feature go/no-go: deciding whether feature X is table-stakes, opportunity, or moat-building.</item>
        <item>Pricing repositioning: anchoring price tier on a fresh per-competitor pricing scrape.</item>
        <item>Pitch deck or investor update: defensible "competitive landscape" slide with sourced rows.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sub-week tactical decisions (single ad copy, single landing-page test) — matrices are too coarse.</item>
        <item>True greenfield with fewer than 3 competitors — feature matrix collapses to 1 column; use jobs-to-be-done.</item>
        <item>Highly regulated B2B (defense, banking core) where competitor data is private and any public pull is misleading.</item>
        <item>Late-stage scaling where customer-success and retention data dominate — feature matrix produces feature-bloat backlog.</item>
        <item>After product-market fit — optimizing on feature matrix is how startups become "Salesforce-but-cheaper" forever.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="landscape-mapping">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every competitor list must include all four types: direct (same solution, same customer), indirect (different solution, same problem), substitute (alternative approach entirely), and potential (could enter market). Reject any list missing substitute and indirect rows.</statement>
        <rationale>Teams default to 3-5 obvious head-on competitors. Substitutes (spreadsheets, email, "do nothing") are the actual churn cause but rarely surface from a Google query — they must be explicitly prompted.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Project management tools: Direct (Asana, Monday, ClickUp), Indirect (Spreadsheets, Slack, Email), Substitute (pen and paper, meeting-based coordination), Potential (AI-native PM tools, no-code builders). Whitespace identified: AI-native PM for solopreneurs.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>Project management tools: Direct only (Asana, Monday, ClickUp, Notion, Linear). Missing indirect, substitute, and potential types — misses the "do nothing" and "spreadsheet" competition that drives 60% of SMB status quo.</note>
      </example>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pre-commit the two positioning axes with named exemplars for each pole before running the matrix. Do not let the agent choose axes that maximize visual separation after seeing the data.</statement>
        <rationale>Post-hoc axis selection produces a map that looks clean but reflects LLM output aesthetics, not buyer decision criteria. Example of correct anchoring: x-axis "simple" = Notion-shaped vs "complex" = Salesforce-shaped.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>After identifying whitespace, pair every candidate whitespace cell with a demand-validation step before acting on it. An empty cell is empty for a reason 80% of the time.</statement>
        <rationale>Whitespace may be empty because: no demand, technically hard, regulated, or unprofitable. A cell being empty is a hypothesis to test, not a greenlight.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require evidence_urls length ≥2 with at least one third-party source per competitor row. Reject any row with only the competitor's own marketing site as evidence.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs paraphrase the competitor's homepage tagline as "positioning" and call the matrix done. Third-party evidence (review site, community thread, screenshot) provides independent verification.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <p>Orchestrator prompt seed pattern: provide category name. Produce 15-20 competitors covering all four types. For each, output a structured row with name, type, founded, funding_usd, team_size, pricing (model, entry_usd, url), positioning (≤140 chars), top_features, and evidence_urls (≥2, at least one third-party). Unknown fields → "unknown". No marketing copy verbatim.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="feature-matrix">
      <rule>
        <statement>For each (feature, competitor) cell: capture status Y|P|N, quality 0-3, and evidence_url. "Y" requires an evidence_url; if no public proof exists, write "N" and add note "no public proof".</statement>
        <rationale>Evidence URL per cell (not per row) eliminates ~80% of the hallucination class. Without it, agents fill 100% of cells with Y even when the feature is undocumented.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Add a quality column (0-3) per cell in addition to Y/P/N. Quality 0 = feature exists but unusable; 3 = best-in-class implementation.</statement>
        <rationale>Y/N hides quality differences — "their search is checkbox-Yes but unusable" looks like parity without the quality column. Catching this stops false feature-parity conclusions.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Allow "unknown" as a valid status for cells where no public proof exists. Require ≥80% known cells to ship the report; below that threshold, flag for primary research.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents fill cells even when no proof exists, defaulting to "N". An explicit "unknown" status distinguishes "we checked and found nothing" from "we didn't check".</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="gap-validation-critic">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run a gap-validator critic after the feature matrix with a forced ≥40% skip budget. For each candidate gap, answer three questions: (1) Why does no competitor have it? (technical/regulatory/unprofitable/unaware). (2) Do customers actually want it? (review quotes, forum links, search volume). (3) Can we build it materially better? Verdict: pursue | investigate | skip. Default = skip when any answer is weak.</statement>
        <rationale>Default LLM tone is helpful — agents recommend every gap as an opportunity. The forced skip budget (≥40%) and adversarial three-question test counter pursuit-bias systematically.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Pair feature-gap identification with review-mining (G2/Reddit top-5 complaints per competitor) before validating. A gap nobody complains about is rarely a real gap.</statement>
        <rationale>Review-mining gives demand-side evidence for whether a gap matters to buyers; without it, gap-validation answers question (2) with "seems likely" rather than "50+ feature requests".</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Maintain a kill-list of gaps marked "skip" with reasons. The orchestrator must not re-recommend a killed gap in future runs without new evidence.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a persistent kill-list, the same low-quality gaps get re-proposed every quarter and consume review cycles that should be spent on new discoveries.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Before filling the feature matrix, merge synonyms: "AI search", "semantic search", "natural-language search" all refer to the same capability. Run a synonym-merge pass before the matrix filler runs.</statement>
        <rationale>Without synonym merging, a single capability splits across 3-4 rows with inconsistent Y/N/P values, making the matrix impossible to aggregate.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="evidence-discipline">
      <rule>
        <statement>Date every competitive report as competitive-analysis-YYYY-MM-DD.md. Store in version control so quarterly re-runs produce diffable deltas. The deltas are the actual decision input, not the absolute values.</statement>
        <rationale>A one-time matrix decays in 3-6 months; without a re-run cadence the analysis becomes a stale anchor that biases decisions long after market conditions changed.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Visualping the top-5 competitor pricing pages weekly. A weekly diff on pricing pages provides 80% of the "competitive monitoring" value for minimal cost.</statement>
        <rationale>Pricing changes are the highest-severity competitive event; daily manual checking is impractical, while a weekly automated diff catches changes within the relevant decision window.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Never act on a whitespace cell found in the current session. Log it, validate against demand signals (review mining or interview transcripts), decide in the next run.</statement>
        <rationale>A 2-week sanity gap prevents impulsive roadmap additions based on a single session's gap analysis that may be incomplete or based on missing evidence.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating the competitive analysis as a standing document rather than a dated snapshot.</description>
        <reason>A feature matrix without a capture date is an undated fact claim that degrades silently. Readers cannot tell if they are looking at last week's reality or last year's.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running the feature matrix without synonym merging across competitor feature names.</description>
        <reason>The same capability under different names produces multiple rows with conflicting Y/N/P values, making aggregation impossible and gap identification unreliable.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Treating listed prices on enterprise tiers as ACVs for B2B pricing analysis.</description>
        <reason>"Talk to Sales" tiers are anchors, not ACVs — actual discounts can be 50-80% off list. Tag these rows with confidence: low, and cross-reference with G2 reviewer-reported pricing.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Marketing-page parroting: LLM paraphrases the competitor's homepage tagline as "positioning" without checking third-party sources.</description>
        <reason>Force evidence_urls length ≥2 with at least one third-party source. Homepage taglines are marketing copy, not observable positioning in buyer perception.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Numeric hallucination: funding totals, ARR, headcount fabricated without source_url.</description>
        <reason>Reject any numeric field without source_url. "Unknown" is the correct output when API access is absent, not a plausible invention.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Optimistic gap recommendations: LLM default helpful tone recommends every gap as an opportunity without adversarial review.</description>
        <reason>The gap-validator critic with a forced skip budget ≥40% is non-negotiable. Without it, the gap list becomes a feature-bloat backlog.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Token blowup from passing full G2 review HTML to the matrix filler.</description>
        <reason>Never paste full review HTML into the matrix-filler. The review-miner must distill to top-5 complaints per competitor first, then pass the distillation.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Human-in-the-loop checkpoint missing: gap list becomes spec input without founder review of the kill-list rationale.</description>
        <reason>Agents under-skip (helpful bias), founders over-skip (loss aversion) — the diff between their lists is the real shortlist. Skip the checkpoint and you get either feature bloat or missed opportunities.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations">
      <list>
        <item>Direct-only blindness. Teams default to the 3-5 obvious head-on competitors and miss substitutes (spreadsheets, email, "do nothing") which are the actual churn cause.</item>
        <item>Static snapshots. A one-time matrix decays in 3-6 months; without a re-run cadence the decisions made off it become stale anchors.</item>
        <item>Feature-checkbox theater. "Has Y/Partial/No" hides quality differences (their search is checkbox-Yes but unusable; ours is Yes and great). Force a 0-3 quality column or N-day-old screenshot link per cell.</item>
        <item>Whitespace fallacy. An empty 2x2 cell is empty for a reason 80% of the time (no demand, hard to build, regulated, unprofitable). Whitespace MUST be paired with a demand-validation step.</item>
        <item>Pricing pages lie. Listed prices ≠ negotiated prices for B2B; agent-only pulls under-report enterprise discounts and over-report SMB ACV.</item>
        <item>LLM source-bias. Agents cite the company's own marketing site as evidence of "feature: Yes" — needs cross-source rule (review site + community thread + screenshot).</item>
        <item>Competitor list survivorship. G2/Capterra rank by paid placement, not adoption. Crunchbase indexes funded only — bootstrapped competitors disappear.</item>
        <item>Substitutes are unsearchable. "Slack vs Email" rarely surfaces from a Google query; must come from user-interview transcripts.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Run as a fan-out / fan-in pipeline keyed on the competitors research mode. An orchestrator (faion-research-agent --mode=competitors) emits a frontier list of 15-20 candidates from seed sources (G2, Capterra, Product Hunt category, Crunchbase, "{category} alternatives" SERPs, "vs {seed}" SERPs). Per-competitor collectors hydrate a structured row (founded, funding, team, pricing, positioning, top features). A separate feature-matrix agent fans out across the top-5 cell-by-cell, fills the Y/P/N grid plus a 0-3 quality score and a per-cell evidence URL. A gap-validation critic interrogates every candidate gap with three questions (intentional? wanted? buildable better?) and rejects ≥40% of them by default to counter pursuit-bias. All output goes to .aidocs/product_docs/competitive-analysis.md keyed by run-date so deltas stay diffable.</p>
      <prompt purpose="orchestrator">
        <![CDATA[
You are the competitor-orchestrator. Seed: "{CATEGORY}".
Step 1: Produce 15-20 competitors covering Direct/Indirect/Substitute/Potential.
Step 2: For each, output ONLY this row:
{
  "name":"", "type":"direct|indirect|substitute|potential",
  "founded":"", "funding_usd":0, "team_size":0,
  "pricing":{"model":"", "entry_usd":0, "url":""},
  "positioning":"<=140 chars",
  "top_features":["",""],
  "evidence_urls":["","",""]
}
Rules: every numeric or claim cites a URL. Unknown -> "unknown". No marketing copy verbatim.
        ]]>
      </prompt>
      <prompt purpose="feature-matrix-filler">
        <![CDATA[
You are the feature-matrix-filler. Features list: {LIST}. Competitors: {LIST}.
For each (feature, competitor) cell return:
{"feature":"", "competitor":"", "status":"Y|P|N",
 "quality":0-3, "evidence_url":"", "notes":"<=80 chars"}
"Y" requires evidence_url; if no evidence, write "N" and add note "no public proof".
        ]]>
      </prompt>
      <prompt purpose="gap-validator-critic">
        <![CDATA[
You are the gap-validator-critic. Candidate gap: "{GAP}".
Answer (with sources):
1. Why does no competitor have it? (technical / regulatory / unprofitable / unaware)
2. Do customers actually want it? (review quotes, forum links, search volume)
3. Can we build it materially better? (our advantage, in one sentence)
Verdict: pursue | investigate | skip. Default = skip when any answer is weak.
        ]]>
      </prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-services">
      <p>Key CLI tools: gh search repos/users (OSS competitor proxy: stars, forks, contributors), crunchbase-cli (funding, founders, headcount), similarweb-cli (traffic/engagement/referrers), builtwith-cli (tech-stack adoption), producthunt-graphql (category leaderboards), g2-scraper/capterra-scraper (review pulls — pair with rotating proxy), praw (Reddit subreddit + thread search; pip install praw), playwright/playwright-mcp (screenshot pricing pages, archive into evidence/), single-file-cli (save competitor page as single HTML; npm i -g single-file-cli), whoxy-cli/whois (founding signal, domain lineage), wayback-machine-downloader (pricing/positioning history; gem install wayback_machine_downloader), searxng (self-hosted federated search for alternatives queries), WebSearch/WebFetch (Claude Code built-in agent web access for ad-hoc rows), pandoc+csvkit (convert competitive matrix between md/csv/xlsx).</p>
      <p>Key services: Crunchbase (SaaS, API paid — funding, headcount, founders), PitchBook (SaaS enterprise, private-company revenue), G2/Capterra/TrustRadius (SaaS, limited API/scrape — reviews), Product Hunt (free GraphQL, alternatives + launch dates), Similarweb (SaaS, paid — traffic momentum), Semrush/Ahrefs (SaaS paid — keyword overlap, ad spend), Klue/Crayon/Kompyte (CI platforms, page-change tracking, battlecards), Visualping (SaaS, diff competitor pricing pages), Wayback Machine (free, pricing/positioning lineage), Perplexity/Tavily/Exa (LLM-search for cited evidence rows).</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Force the four types. Reject any competitor list missing substitute and indirect rows — that is where churn lives.</item>
        <item>Evidence URL per cell, not per row. A feature-matrix cell without evidence_url is implicitly "N". This single rule kills 80% of the hallucination class.</item>
        <item>Quality column, not just Y/P/N. Add 0-3 per cell so "feature exists but unusable" stops looking like parity.</item>
        <item>Diff-friendly snapshots. Date every report; store as competitive-analysis-YYYY-MM-DD.md. The deltas (price changed, feature shipped, headcount jumped) are the actual decision input on rerun.</item>
        <item>Pair feature-gap with review-mining. A gap nobody complains about in G2/Reddit is rarely a real gap — auto-pull complaints first, derive feature gaps second.</item>
        <item>Visualping the pricing page. A weekly diff on top-5 pricing pages is a free 80% of "competitive monitoring".</item>
        <item>Keep a kill-list. Gaps marked "skip" with a reason persist across sessions; the orchestrator must not re-recommend them.</item>
        <item>Personal-fit / strategic-fit filter before whitespace shipping. A real gap that does not match our distribution / skill / brand is still a skip.</item>
        <item>2-week sanity gap on whitespace. Never act on a "whitespace cell" found this session — log it, validate against demand signals, decide next run.</item>
        <item>Anchor pricing pulls with a screenshot. Playwright/single-file the pricing page to evidence/ — protects against "their site changed before review".</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/landscape-table.md" purpose="Competitor landscape table: direct/indirect/substitute/potential with founding/funding/pricing/positioning"/>
      <template path="templates/feature-matrix.md" purpose="Feature matrix with Y/P/N, 0-3 quality score, evidence_url, and gap-validation block"/>
      <template path="templates/competitor-signals.py" purpose="Multi-source per-competitor signal collector: HN, GitHub, ProductHunt, Wayback Machine"/>
    </templates>

